			<div class="content" id="post-content-1511777">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Actually… They've had diodes for a long time, and could make them emit light, so it's not a stretch that's how they'd be described. The practical use of the LCD came MUCH later.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>LCDs don't bear much resemblance to LEDs, and the science of liquid crystals wouldn't have been novel - if the dude said &quot;that's a liquid crystal display,&quot; SCP researchers would reasonably be able to verify that. Even if he didn't, dismantling it would still yield polarized layers, a backlight, and a flexible sheet with goo in it - nothing at all like early LED prototypes.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Depends what type of phone it is. Early camera-phones didn't have THAT great a display.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>He's from 2008 or later. The phone's a slider with a full keyboard. This ain't some ancient Nokia.</p>

